cc16c760-f11a-4fb5-a036-e2fb7f6ef6bc.03e72cb3-3966-4e2a-b8c6-29a2de93d423.description=
Check the current date and time, and returns a java DateAndTime formatted string of it. If locale is specified, it will return the date and time string based on the locale.Otherwise, default locale will be used.

Inputs\:
    localeLang - The locale language for date and time string. 
Examples\:  en, ja, unix.
    localeCountry - The locale country for date and time string. For example, US or JP. If localeLang is not specified, this input will be ingored.

Result\:
    Current date and time.

Responses\:
    success - Date/time retrieved successfully.   
    failure - Date/time could not be retrieved.

Notes.
    1. If localeLang is 'unix' the localeCountry input is ignored and the result will be the current UNIX timestamp.

cc16c760-f11a-4fb5-a036-e2fb7f6ef6bc.4d969ac6-15fc-4890-b6c7-88cf5c0df8ee.description=
Runs the requested SQL Command, returns the number of row(s) affected and any lateral effect.

Inputs\:
host	- Hostname or IP address of the SQL Server.
username	- The username of the SQL or Windows user credentials to login to the SQL Server.  If use Windows authentication, username input should be in the format like\: domain\username. 
password	- Password of the user account.
instance        - The named instance of SQL Server. Leave it blank for default instance.
dbPort	- The port on which the SQL Server database service is listening on.
database 	- The name of the database to run the command on.
authType	- Whether Windows authentication or SQL authentication should be used. Default is SQL.
command 	- The actual SQL command to run (either T-SQL, Stored Procedure, or Extended procedure).
timeout 	- Seconds to wait before timing out the SQL command execution. It defaults to 30 seconds.

Result\:
The number of rows affected.

Extra results\:
outputText -	 Output result for the command (if this is the case).

Responses\:
success 	- The command was successful.
failure 	- There was a problem running the command.

Notes\:
1. When informational commands (like dbcc) are run through the command, end the command with "with tableresults" in order to populate the outputText output with the obtained result.
2. Use the Sql Query operation instead of Sql Command when Select queries are to be run.
3. Please refer to the Notes in the Microsoft SQL folder description for the general integration information of Microsoft SQL Server.
cc16c760-f11a-4fb5-a036-e2fb7f6ef6bc.5edb708f-f7ec-40e2-8fb5-5ee9aac03675.description=Retrieves a system account username and password and stores the values as flow variables. Inputs\: accountName - The name of the system account. Starting with OO Platform version 10.20, the relative path of the system account can also be used. flowVariable - The flow variables prefix to store the system account into. The operation will receive one input with the flow variable name to assign to, but will actually assign the account to two separate variables. So if the input flowVar was "sysAcct" then two flow vars will be created "sysAcctUsername" and "sysAcctPassword". Results\: Result - A message indicating if the operation was successful or not. Responses\: success - The operation completed as stated in the description. failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully. cc16c760-f11a-4fb5-a036-e2fb7f6ef6bc.a18b25cb-45ce-445d-a2dd-71e48c799829.description=
This operation converts the date input value from one date/time format (specified by dateFormat) to another date/time format (specified by outFormat) using locale settings (language and country).
You can use the flow "Get Current Date and Time" to check upon the default date/time format from the Java environement.  

Inputs\:
    date - The date to parse/convert.
    dateFormat - The format of the input date.
Default value\: default date/time format from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS date/time format)
Examples\: unix, yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX, h\:mm a
    dateLocaleLang - The locale language for input dateFormat string. It will be ignored if dateFormat is empty. 
Default value\: default locale language from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale language)
Examples\: en, ja
    dateLocaleCountry - The locale country for input dateFormat string. It will be ignored if dateFormat is empty or dateLocaleLang is empty.
Default value\: default locale country from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale country)
Example\: US, FR
    outFormat - The format of the output date/time.
Default value\: default date/time format from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS date/time format)
Examples\: unix, yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX, h\:mm a
    outLocaleLang - The locale language for output string. It will be ignored if outFormat is empty. 
Default value\: default locale language from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale language)
Examples\: en, ja
    outLocaleCountry - The locale country for output string. It will be ignored if outFormat is empty or outLocaleLang is empty.
Default value\: default locale country from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale country)
Example\: US, FR

Results\:
    returnResult - The date in the new format.

Responses\:
    success - The date was converted.
    failure - The date could not be converted.

Notes\:
    1. If default locale language from the Java environement is English, the input dateFormat is empty and the input outFormat is empty, the input date should be in the format of "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the user specifies dateFormat as "dd-MM-yyyy HH\:mm\:ss", the input date should be in the format of "13-07-2006 10\:04\:08". If the input outFormat is empty, the result will be "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the input outFormat is "yyyy-MM-dd", the result will be "2006-07-13". The dateFormat for "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:078 AM" is "MMM dd, yyyy HH\:mm\:ss a".
    2. Note that the dateFormat and outFormat inputs are case sensitive. 'M' is used for months representation and 'm' for minutes.
    3. Within date and time pattern strings, unquoted letters from 'A' to 'Z' and from 'a' to 'z' are interpreted as pattern letters representing the components of a date or time string. Text can be quoted using single quotes (') to avoid interpretation. "''" represents a single quote. All other characters are not interpreted; they're simply copied into the output string during formatting or matched against the input string during parsing. The following pattern letters are defined (all other characters from 'A' to 'Z' and from 'a' to 'z' are reserved)\:

Letter	Date or Time Component			Presentation		Examples
G	Era designator				Text		AD
y	Year				Year		1996; 96
Y	Week year				Year		2009; 09
M	Month in year				Month		July; Jul; 07
w	Week in year				Number		27
W	Week in month				Number		2
D	Day in year				Number		189
d	Day in month				Number		10
F	Day of week in month			Number		2
E	Day name in week			Text		Tuesday; Tue
u	Day number of week (1 \= Monday, ..., 7 \= Sunday)	Number		1
a	Am/pm marker				Text		PM
H	Hour in day (0-23)			Number		0
k	Hour in day (1-24)			Number		24
K	Hour in am/pm (0-11)			Number		0
h	Hour in am/pm (1-12)			Number		12
m	Minute in hour				Number		30
s	Second in minute			Number		55
S	Millisecond				Number		978
z	Time zone				General time zone	Pacific Standard Time; PST; GMT-08\:00
Z	Time zone				RFC 822 time zone	-800
X	Time zone				ISO 8601 time zone	-08; -0800; -08\:00
Special case\:
unix	Unix timestamp			Number		1384326000

Examples for the date 2001-07-04 12\:08\:56 in U.S. Pacific Time\:

Date			DateFromat			DateLocaleLang	DateLocaleCountry
2001.07.04 AD at 12\:08\:56 PDT	yyyy.MM.dd G 'at' HH\:mm\:ss z		en		US
Wed, Jul 4, '01			EEE, MMM d, ''yy		en		US
2001-07-04T12\:08\:56.235+0700	yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSZ	en		US
2001-07-04T12\:08\:56.235-07\:00	yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX	en		US
1309781336			unix			-		-
cc16c760-f11a-4fb5-a036-e2fb7f6ef6bc.f0db039e-30e2-4364-b2e0-86b84995c89a.description=
This step will insert the ddr records into automation db

Inputs\:
    host - Hostname or IP address of the SQL Server.
    username	- The username of the SQL or Windows user credentials to login to the SQL Server.  If use Windows authentication, username input should be in the format like\: domain\username. 
    password	- Password of the user account.
    instance - The named instance of SQL Server. Leave it blank for default instance.
    dbPort - The port on which the SQL Server database service is listening on.
Default value\: 1433
    database - The name of the database to run the command on.
    authType	- Whether Windows authentication or SQL authentication should be used. 
Valid values\: sql, window
Default value\: sql
    query - The SQL query to run (either T-SQL, Stored Procedure, or Extended procedure).
    save - If true, saves the query execution result and database connection in session context.
Default value\: true
    delimiter - The delimiter to use between columns in returnResult and columnNames.
    keyName - The name of a key to help keep multiple query results distinct.
    multipleActiveResultSets - Allow multiple DataReaders open concurrently on the same connection.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    timeout - Seconds to wait before timing out the SQL query execution.
Default value\: 30

Results\:
   ddrRecords
   insertDBFailFlag
  errorMessages

Responses\:
    more items - More rows are available for retrieval.
    no more items - No more rows are available.
    failure - Failed to execute the query.

Notes\: 
1. Refer to the Notes in the Microsoft SQL folder description. 
2. This operation runs SQL SELECT statement. To run SQL command  (like INSERT, UPDATE or DELETE), use the 'SQL Command' or 'SQL Script' operation.
3. To get the query result, set the value of the  input to 'true'.
4. The database connection will close automatically after the query has executed if you set the value of the  input to 'false', or of the operation returns a 'failure' or 'no more items' response.
5. 'SQL Query' is an iterative operation, so while the operation's response is 'more items', the database connection stays open. It closes when the response is 'no more items'. If you want to exit the loop before reaching the 'no more items' response, close the database connection using the 'Close Database Connection' operation. For the deprecated 'SQL Query (1)' and 'Get Next Sql Row' operations, the database connection stays open while 'Get Next Sql Row' responds 'has more rows'. It closes when the response is 'no more rows'. If you want to exit the loop before reaching the 'no more rows' response, close the database connection using the 'Close Database Connection' operation.
6. If the 'SQL Query' operation is used with different query commands in different steps in a flow, specify a different key value in each step to guarantee the uniqueness of the retrieve query results.
